# Cursor Rules for Personal Blog

## Project Overview

This is a personal blog built with Next.js 15 and MDX. The site is deployed at www.waynewen.com via Vercel with GitHub integration.

## Tech Stack

- Next.js 15 (App Router)
- React 19
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS
- MDX for blog content
- Vercel for deployment

## Package Manager

Use **npm** exclusively. Do not use yarn, pnpm, or bun.

```bash
npm install      # Install dependencies
npm run dev      # Development server
npm run build    # Production build
npm run start    # Production server
npm run lint     # Linting
```

## Project Structure

```
src/
├── app/           # Next.js App Router pages
├── components/    # React components
│   └── mdx/       # MDX-specific components
├── config/        # Site and blog configuration
├── content/       # MDX blog posts
│   └── blog/      # Blog post files
├── fonts/         # Custom fonts (Atkinson Hyperlegible)
└── lib/           # Utility functions
    └── mdx/       # MDX processing utilities
```

## Coding Conventions

Follow Next.js best practices:

- Use functional components with hooks
- Use named exports for components
- Use PascalCase for component files and names
- Use camelCase for utility functions and variables
- Prefer TypeScript interfaces over types for object shapes
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling (no CSS modules or styled-components)

## Content

Blog posts are MDX files in `src/content/blog/` with frontmatter:

```mdx
---
title: "Post Title"
date: "YYYY-MM-DD"
description: "Brief description"
---
```

## Scope

This repository is exclusively for the personal blog. Do not add features unrelated to blogging functionality.

## Key Files

- `src/config/site.ts` - Site-wide configuration
- `src/config/blog.ts` - Blog-specific configuration
- `src/lib/mdx/utils.ts` - MDX processing utilities
- `src/components/mdx/` - Custom MDX components

## Git Commit Messages

Follow the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/) specification:

```
<type>[optional scope]: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

### Types

- `feat:` - New feature (correlates with MINOR in SemVer)
- `fix:` - Bug fix (correlates with PATCH in SemVer)
- `docs:` - Documentation only changes
- `style:` - Code style changes (formatting, whitespace)
- `refactor:` - Code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
- `perf:` - Performance improvement
- `test:` - Adding or updating tests
- `chore:` - Maintenance tasks, dependency updates
- `ci:` - CI/CD configuration changes
- `build:` - Build system or external dependency changes

### Examples

```bash
feat: add syntax highlighting for code blocks
fix: resolve hydration mismatch in theme switcher
docs: update README with deployment instructions
refactor(mdx): simplify mermaid component logic
feat!: change API response format (breaking change)
```

### Rules

- Use lowercase for type and description
- No period at the end of the description
- Use imperative mood ("add" not "added" or "adds")
- Keep first line under 72 characters
- Add body for complex changes explaining what and why

## Pull Request Summary

Always format PR summaries in **Markdown** with the following structure:

```markdown
## Summary
- Bullet points describing the key changes (1-3 items)

## Changes

**Section Name**
- Detailed change description
- Another change

**Another Section**
- More changes as needed

## Test plan
- [ ] Checkbox items for testing the changes
- [ ] Another test case
```

### PR Guidelines

- Write clear, concise summaries focused on "what" and "why"
- Group related changes under descriptive section headers
- Use bullet points for readability
- Include test plan with actionable verification steps
- Reference related issues if applicable (e.g., `Fixes #123`)
